TY  - JOUR
AU  - Sequeira, Sandra
AU  - Nunn, Nathan
AU  - Qian, Nancy
T1  - Immigrants and the Making of America
PY  - 2020
Y1  - 2020/01/01
DO  - 10.1093/restud/rdz003
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 87
IS  - 1
SP  - 382
EP  - 419
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - We study the effects of European immigration to the U.S. during the Age of Mass Migration (1850–1920) on economic prosperity. Exploiting cross-county variation in immigration that arises from the interaction of fluctuations in aggregate immigrant flows and of the gradual expansion of the railway network, we find that counties with more historical immigration have higher income, less poverty, less unemployment, higher rates of urbanization, and greater educational attainment today. The long-run effects seem to capture the persistence of short-run benefits, including greater industrialization, increased agricultural productivity, and more innovation.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdz003
ER  - 



